info: This corpus is an automatically annotated version of data from the Parallel Bible Corpus (Mayer & Cysouw 2014) that has been reduced in scope for the purposes of crosslinguistic research. Metadata from the original PBC file is included in this dict for reference, as well as the license information and the automatic POS annotations. The first three characters of the filename corresponds to the ISO 639-3 code for the respective language. The `tagged` key in this dict contains a list of lists, with the first item in each sublist being the verse number (following PBC convention) and the second being a list of tuples in [word, POS] format where `unk` represents unknown tags.
license: This data is shared under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license, and can be used solely for research purposes. The data is a selection of non-contiguous verses from a translation for the purpose of crosslinguistic research. Copyright of selected verses of each translation is retained by the original copyright holders.
metadata: # copyright_long: The Wanchos are the tribal people inhabiting the South-Western part of the Tirap district in Arunachal Pradesh a state in the Northeast India. They have a population of 35,000 having a literacy rate of 45%. They are ethnically related to the Noktes in Arunachal Pradesh and the Konyak in Nagaland. They belong to the language group of the Tibeto-Burman family. Initially, the Wanchos were the followers of animism and still majority of these loyally retained the belief of animism. However, with the Baptist mission and the Roman Catholics operating this mission work among the Wanchos since 1960 and 1974, the Christian population has been increasing rapidly. The Bible Society published the first New Testament in 2002 and the complete Wancho Naga Bible was published in 2012. This translation, published by the Bible Society of India, was published in 2012. If you are interested in obtaining a printed copy, please contact the Bible Society of India at www.bsind.org
